<seg id=1> Reporting the Rape of Chinese Women in May Riot, One Journalist Summoned to Court for Interrogation by Indonesian Police </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AFP, Jakarta) "Journalists Protection Committee", an international organization to guard the freedom of press, expressed its astonishment on Indonesian police's summon of a journalist who reported the rape of Chinese women in May riot. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> New York-based Journalists Protection Committee said that the journalist who worked for the magazine "Jakarta--Jakarta" was summoned to the police headquaters for interrogation on Thursday. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The committee said that Gu Wanna cited a raped woman's talk in a report published in July. </seg>
<seg id=5> "New York Times" also cited the talk of the same victim in a report published on June 10th. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> In the letter written to Indonesian President B. J. Habibie, the committee said issuing subpoena is "the first step taken by the police for future accusation". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> The committee was "very worried that the citation of such laws would leave negative impact on freedom of speech". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> What the committee referred to was Indonesian Islam Organization's pressure on the government, which requested the government to arrest Gu Wanna under No. 156 clause of the Criminal Law. </seg>
<seg id=9> The clause prohibits slander on religious groups. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> International Independent Journalists Association also protested against the police's summon of Gu Wanna. </seg>
<seg id=11> It said that it would "make a bad example, resulting in undermining of the bigger press freedom the media enjoyed since the fall of the fomer president Suharto". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> The Journalists Protection Committee appealed to Habibie to "stop turning against Gu Wanna", and requested every side involved settle the dispute in a civil court. </seg>
<seg id=13> It also called on all sides to "make greatest efforts possible to do away with the slander clause in Indonesian Criminal Law. </seg>
</p>
